1. The Core Architecture: Managed Code
In an interview, a common "warm-up" question is: "What is the difference between Managed and Unmanaged code?"
C# is a Managed Language. This means you don't talk directly to the hardware. Instead, your code runs inside a "sandbox" called the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
The Compilation Process
When you hit "Build" in Visual Studio, your C# doesn't immediately become machine code (0s and 1s). It goes through two steps:
C# Source Code ---> Compiled into Intermediate Language (IL).
IL Code ---> The Just-In-Time (JIT) Compiler turns it into Machine Code right when the app runs.

2. DataTypes in C# 
- In C#, data types are primarily divided into two main categories: Value Types and Reference Types, with a third category for Pointer Types used in specific scenarios. C# is a strongly-typed language, meaning every variable must be declared with a specific data type. 

2.1 Value Types
Value types store the actual data directly in memory (typically on the stack). When you assign a value type variable to another, a copy of the value is created. All built-in numeric types are value types and derive from System.ValueType, which in turn derives from System.Object

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                 STACK MEMORY
        (Stores Value Types Directly)

        ┌───────────────────────────┐
        │ int number = 10;          │
        │ ┌───────────────┐         │
        │ │ number : 10   │         │
        │ └───────────────┘         │
        │                           │
        │ bool isActive = true;     │
        │ ┌───────────────┐         │
        │ │ isActive:true │         │
        │ └───────────────┘         │
        │                           │
        │ char grade = 'A';         │
        │ ┌───────────────┐         │
        │ │ grade : 'A'   │         │
        │ └───────────────┘         │
        │                           │
        │ double price = 99.5;      │
        │ ┌───────────────┐         │
        │ │ price : 99.5  │         │
        │ └───────────────┘         │
        └───────────────────────────┘
